The term “τ0” is the average lifetime of nanocomposites in the absence of quencher (determined as 4.8 ns [35]). Using the values of Ksv and τ0, the value of Kq was determined as 5.2 × 1012 M−1 s−1, which is greater than the maximum diffusion collision quenching constant (∼1010 M−1 s−1) [55]. This indicates predominant role of static quenching mechanism (complex formation in the ground state) in the PA detection by PEG@SiONCs rather than dynamic quenching. Additional set of experiments were carried out to ascertain the quenching mechanism, which are described as follows. The differentiation between static and dynamic quenching can be discerned based on their distinct reliance on various factors such as temperature, viscosity, or alternatively, through lifetime measurements [55]. At high temperature, diffusion is faster, which increases the probability of collisional quenching. Also, dissociation of weakly bound complexes would be more at higher temperatures, resulting in reduced levels of static quenching. Fig. 4
                        a shows the plot of F0/F versus [PA, μM] at different temperatures (25, 45, and 55 °C). It can be seen that the variation in the slopes (on linear fitting the data) is insignificant and no particular trend was observed. This is also evident from the KSV and Kq values for plots corresponding to higher temperature measurements (provided in Table 1
                        ). This experiment rules out the possibility of static quenching-based mechanism responsible for the observed “PL turn-off” in PEG@SiONCs when exposed to PA.
